Basically, I think it is to no ones surprise that most fictional species are humanoid at least in the facial and/or body section; it is easier to write about what we know, and thus the more deviant we stray from the bipedal, four limbs, flat face anatomical blueprint the more you will find species be described as feral, monstrous, foreign (from another dimension) and extremity difficult to communicate with at and level of intelligence. This limitation of our fictional species is most prominent and influential in live action where it is exceeding more difficult to project human facial/body expressions both physically and conceptually on non-humanoid fictional species. As a general rule it seems the more non-humanoid the facial region of the fictional alien species, the more stiffer and stoic it would appear on screen. Anthro character have been successfully portrayed with human expressions in the cartoon industries, but I think that is because of the simple design of the characters and how far remove the antrho characters designs are from their feral counter part, tthat one cannot immediately tell how anatomically different these cartoon animals are from their counterparts (cont.)

Anonymous Thu 01 Oct 2020 11:19:54 No.33136351 Report

>>33131826
>how close one could get into portraying a non-humanoid anthro species (at least in the facial area) to be able to facially and bodily communicate with humans.
The farther away from the face of the person being facial captured you go, the more it's a translation of expression rather than a direct 1:1 performance. Hell, any and all facial capture isn't ever 1:1 what the actor was doing anyway as there's a cleanup stage no mater what kind of tech you have that's required as what data you get in won't be clean enough for actual production use. Which means there's gonna be an animators touch to any sort of facial capture you do, which is why when you listen to the behind the scenes of these movies, it's always in terms of "How much of the original actors performance we can capture/retain." Because the less capable of the production, the closer it is to straight animating the face by hand anyway.
So if that's what they do for human faces, you can only imagine what it's like when we get actual non-humans into the mix. They could make a proper translation layer for the facial features of the non-human to the human actor, but that's work for something they're worried would look 'uncanny'. You know all the promo stuff for the Hobbit where they had Benedict Cumberbatch rolling around the floor doing performance capture for Smaug, pic related? None of that is actually used in the movie. None of it. It was used as reference for the animators to animate Smaug the traditional way, as a 3D in-scene reference is a million times better than the 2D video recordings you usually have, but what was captured was never actually directly utilized in the movies.
We have the tech now to do slightly less sophisticated versions of this sort of thing at home, I really hope someone goes ham at some point and does this properly at some point. You can get basically studio grade renders out of Blender now-a-days, it just takes someone determined enough to put them together.
